Try to fix this issue this way:

```
@JsonTypeInfo(use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.NAME, include = JsonTypeInfo.As.PROPERTY, property = &quot;type&quot;)
@JsonSubTypes({
    @JsonSubTypes.Type(value = Child1.class, name = &quot;child1&quot;),
    @JsonSubTypes.Type(value = Child2.class, name = &quot;child2&quot;)
})
class Parent {
    String parentId;
}

```

It is Jackson annotations `@JsonTypeInfo` and `@JsonSubTypes` which you should use on your parent class.

The issue you are facing is related to deserialization of the JSON request into your `GeneralRequest` object. Spring Boot&#39;s default JSON deserialization may not be able to determine which child class (`Child1` or `Child2`) to instantiate based on the JSON structure you provided. To fix this issue, you can use Jackson&#39;s `@JsonTypeInfo` annotation to specify the subtype information in your JSON payload.

Here&#39;s how you can modify your DTO classes and request JSON:

1. Update your `Parent` class to include `@JsonTypeInfo` annotation and `@JsonSubTypes` annotation to specify the subtypes.

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonSubTypes;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonTypeInfo;

@Data
@NoArgsConstructor
@JsonTypeInfo(
  use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.NAME,
  include = JsonTypeInfo.As.PROPERTY,
  property = &quot;type&quot;
)
@JsonSubTypes({
  @JsonSubTypes.Type(value = Child1.class, name = &quot;child1&quot;),
  @JsonSubTypes.Type(value = Child2.class, name = &quot;child2&quot;)
})
class Parent {
  String parendId;
}
```

2. Update your `GeneralRequest` class to include a `type` property indicating the child class.

```java
@Data
@NoArgsConstructor
class GeneralRequest {
  Parent child1;
  Parent child2;
}
```

3. Modify your JSON request to include the `type` property for each child.

```json
{
  &quot;child1&quot;: {
    &quot;type&quot;: &quot;child1&quot;,
    &quot;parentId&quot;: &quot;P1&quot;,
    &quot;childId&quot;: &quot;C1&quot;,
    &quot;childName&quot;: &quot;C1++&quot;
  },
  &quot;child2&quot;: {
    &quot;type&quot;: &quot;child2&quot;,
    &quot;parentId&quot;: &quot;P1&quot;,
    &quot;childId&quot;: &quot;C2&quot;,
    &quot;childName&quot;: &quot;C2++&quot;,
    &quot;school&quot;: &quot;schoolname&quot;
  }
}
```

With these changes, Jackson will be able to determine the correct subtype to instantiate based on the `type` property in the JSON request, and the deserialization should work as expected in your Spring Boot controller.

